<br>
I was in a group in Lower Guk consisting of 2 rogues, a bard, and 2 clerics.  There had recently been some fierce fighting including a death (bad when a room spawns and everyone is at 10m), but now we're all sitting at full mana and full health.<br>
<br>
The bard wants to pull another room, in which it will be highly dangerous.  A few caster mobs and melee mobs.  The bard and one rogue is gung ho, the clerics are indifferent yet concerned, and the other rogue is adamantly opposed and is convinced we're all going to die.<br>
<br>
So, the rogue who does not want to fight announces that she will not participate in the fight and will watch the rest of the group die if the pull happens.  This causes an argument about if we can win and if it is in poor taste to refuse to fight on one hand, or do a pull that a group member is uncomfortable with.  The gung ho rogue threatens to black list the other rogue.<br>
<br>
The upshot is that the gung ho rogue goes ahead and pulls and it was quite a battle.  More undead froggies than group members.  However, with some extreme risk taking involving blinding and area effect fear, we turned the tables and won quite convincingly in the end.  During the battle, the rogue who was against the pull hid and did not fight anything.  Even at the end of the battle when it was safe and we were mopping up the last couple and could have used her (clerics were low mana and tanks had just enough health to finish things), she refused to help.  She got exp for every kill though, hoping we'd all die.<br>
<br>
After the battle, the victorious tanks announce that the other rogue will be blacklisted for her non-participation and she leaves the group.  Now I got a bit peeved at both rogues during this encounter, but which rogue was really in the wrong here?<br>
